    <!-- What to Look For -->
    <section>
      <h2>What to Look for When Buying Energy Gummies</h2>

      <p>The energy gummy market is flooded with products that overpromise and underdose. Use this checklist to evaluate any product, including ones not on this list.</p>

      <div class="info-cards">
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">1</div>
          <h4>Transparent Label</h4>
          <p>Every active ingredient should list its exact dose. Avoid "proprietary blends" that hide individual amounts. If you cannot see how much caffeine, B12, or CoQ10 is in each serving, move on.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">2</div>
          <h4>Clinically Studied Doses</h4>
          <p>Caffeine: 75-200mg. B12: 1,000-2,500mcg. CoQ10: 100-200mg. Doses significantly below these ranges are unlikely to produce a noticeable effect, regardless of marketing claims.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">3</div>
          <h4>Third-Party Testing</h4>
          <p>USP Verified, NSF Certified for Sport, or Informed Sport. These certifications verify that what is on the label is actually in the product, at the stated dose, without contaminants.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">4</div>
          <h4>Added Sugar Content</h4>
          <p>Most gummies contain 2-4g of added sugar per serving. This is generally acceptable. Avoid products with 6g+ per serving, which adds empty calories and can contribute to energy crashes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">5</div>
          <h4>Match the Mechanism to Your Need</h4>
          <p>Need energy NOW? Choose caffeine. Building baseline energy? Choose B12 or CoQ10. Supporting athletic performance? Choose electrolyte + caffeine combos or beetroot nitric oxide.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-ico">6</div>
          <h4>Cost Per Serving, Not Per Bottle</h4>
          <p>A $12 bottle with 70 servings ($0.17/serving) is far better value than a $20 bottle with 12 servings ($1.67/serving). Always calculate per-serving cost before comparing prices.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Energy Gummies</h2>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do energy gummies actually work?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Energy gummies containing clinically studied ingredients like caffeine (100-200mg), Vitamin B12 (1,000-2,500mcg), or CoQ10 (100-200mg) can meaningfully increase alertness, reduce fatigue, and support cellular energy production. The key is verified dosage. Many products underdose key ingredients — look for transparent labels that list exact amounts, not proprietary blends. Caffeine-based gummies provide immediate results within 20-45 minutes. B-vitamin and CoQ10 formulas build energy over days to weeks of daily use.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>How much caffeine is safe in energy gummies?</summary>
        <p>The FDA considers up to 400mg of caffeine per day safe for most healthy adults. Individual energy gummies typically contain 25-200mg per serving. If you also drink coffee, tea, or other caffeinated beverages, factor those into your daily total. A standard cup of coffee contains 80-100mg, so adding a 100mg caffeine gummy puts you at 180-200mg — well within safe limits. Pregnant or nursing women should limit caffeine to 200mg per day total. Start with a lower-dose gummy if you are caffeine-sensitive.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are energy gummies better than energy drinks?</summary>
        <p>Energy gummies offer several advantages over energy drinks: no sugar crash from high-sugar formulas (many energy drinks contain 30-60g sugar), precise dosing per gummy, portability without liquid, and typically fewer artificial ingredients. However, energy drinks provide hydration and faster absorption since liquids enter the bloodstream more quickly. The best choice depends on your priorities: convenience and clean ingredients favor gummies, hydration and speed favor drinks.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can I take energy gummies every day?</summary>
        <p>B-vitamin and adaptogen-based energy gummies (like OLLY, Vitafusion, Nature Made, and SmartyPants) are generally safe for daily use at recommended doses. Caffeine-based energy gummies can also be taken daily, but monitor your total caffeine intake from all sources and keep it under 400mg per day. If you experience jitters, insomnia, or increased heart rate, reduce your dose. Consult a healthcare provider if you have cardiovascular conditions or take medications that interact with caffeine.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>When should I take energy gummies?</summary>
        <p>For caffeine-based gummies, take them 20-30 minutes before you need the energy boost. Avoid taking caffeine gummies within 6 hours of bedtime, as caffeine has a half-life of approximately 5-6 hours. B-vitamin gummies can be taken any time of day, ideally with a meal for better absorption. For pre-workout energy, take caffeine gummies 30-45 minutes before exercise. CoQ10 and B-complex gummies are best taken in the morning with breakfast as part of a daily routine.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do B12 gummies give you energy if you are not deficient?</summary>
        <p>Vitamin B12 plays a critical role in energy metabolism and red blood cell production. If you are deficient — common in vegans (up to 62% deficiency rate), older adults (up to 30%), and those on metformin or PPIs — supplementation can significantly improve energy levels. If your B12 levels are already adequate, additional supplementation is unlikely to provide a noticeable energy boost because your body excretes excess B12 in urine. A simple blood test from your doctor can determine your B12 status and whether supplementation is warranted.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are energy gummies safe for teens?</summary>
        <p>B-vitamin gummies at standard doses are generally safe for teens aged 14 and older. However, the American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that adolescents avoid caffeine supplements, including caffeinated energy gummies. The AAP suggests teens should not exceed 100mg of caffeine per day. Many caffeine gummies on this list deliver 100-200mg per serving, which could exceed the recommendation in a single dose. Always check the label for caffeine content and consult a pediatrician before giving energy supplements to teenagers.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What is the difference between caffeine gummies and B-vitamin energy gummies?</summary>
        <p>Caffeine gummies provide immediate stimulant energy by blocking adenosine receptors in the brain, producing alertness within 20-45 minutes. The effect peaks at 1-2 hours and fades over 5-6 hours. B-vitamin gummies support long-term cellular energy production through metabolic pathways, particularly the conversion of food into ATP. The effect is not immediate — it builds over days and weeks of daily use, especially if you have a deficiency. Many people benefit from using both: caffeine for acute situations (workouts, early mornings, long drives) and B-vitamins as a daily foundation.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

